subproject.description: The overall illiteracy rate is staggers around 37%, and disaggregated in terms of gender, more women (about 50%) than men (30%) are illiterate. These rates are much lower than those of other countries in Sub-Saharan Africa. Literacy rates for South Africa, Zimbabwe and Kenya are estimated to be at over 80%. It is within this context of extreme vulnerability to diseases and external shocks that the efforts to improve human capital development in Malawi are being seen as critical in reversing the scourges of poverty and exclusion. To its credit, the Government of Malawi with support from UNDP embraced integrated functional literacy and REFLECT in particular, as a participatory methodology which can address both adult illiteracy and livelihood insecurity.
